      Is jiu-jitsu securities fraud?
   =20
 =20

Oh, you know:
=09Every bad thing that happens to a public company is also securities frau=
d.=09Getting beaten up is bad.=09
Mark Zuckerberg=C2=A0getting beat up is probably bad for Meta Platforms Inc=
. =E2=80=9CIf Mr. Zuckerberg were to become unavailable for any reason,=E2=
=80=9D says Meta in its securities filings,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthere could be a =
material adverse impact on our operations.=E2=80=9D For instance if he got =
beat up real bad.=09Therefore Mark Zuckerberg getting beaten up is securiti=
es fraud.

And since Zuckerberg enjoys Brazilian jiu-jitsu, which significantly elevat=
es his risk of getting beaten up,
  [2]
=C2=A0there are arguable securities disclosure concerns. He recently tore a=
 ligament in training and got surgery for it, and Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Alexa=
ndra Barinka wrote last Friday:

There is a serious consideration here about whether Meta Platforms Inc.=E2=
=80=99s co-founder, CEO and controlling shareholder has a duty to disclose =
his MMA [mixed martial arts] activities to investors, particularly if forma=
l contests are in his future. What if it=E2=80=99s worse next time? Zuckerb=
erg posted about his surgery on Instagram, and there was no filing or compa=
ny statement.
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a question of materiality,=E2=80=9D said Bryan Westho=
ff, an attorney at Polsinelli PC. =E2=80=9CIs it material to a reasonable i=
nvestor to know what the executives are doing? Is there danger and uniquene=
ss to it? MMA is something that most of us don=E2=80=99t do."
It=E2=80=99s not that unreasonable to expect Zuckerberg will get injured ag=
ain one day. About three in five MMA fights had at least one injury, accord=
ing to an article published in the Orthopaedic Journal of Sports Medicine t=
hat reviewed 503 amateur and professional contests in 2018 and 2019. Zucker=
berg=E2=80=99s injury was just during training. He tore a ligament in his k=
nee, a joint that one could argue isn=E2=80=99t necessary to run a social m=
edia company (especially if he=E2=80=99s spending time in his virtual reali=
ty metaverse). But what about his brain? Head injuries appear to be higher =
risk if he doesn=E2=80=99t win his fights; of losers=E2=80=99 injuries in t=
he Journal=E2=80=99s review, 17% were concussions.

Look, nobody is more into =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D =
than me, but I can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0really=C2=A0imagine Meta getting sued for=
 this if Zuckerberg gets a concussion. Everyone takes lots of risks in life=
, sometimes accidents happen to CEOs, and those accidents=C2=A0probably=C2=
=A0aren=E2=80=99t actually fraud. (Not legal advice!)
Still, why=C2=A0hasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0Meta added a risk factor for this? Not =
because it is legally required, I mean, but just because it would be fun fo=
r the lawyers? Add a sentence to the risk factors like =E2=80=9Cour CEO lik=
es to go to gyms to get punched in the face, and if he gets punched really =
hard in the wrong part of his face then we may be unable to execute on our =
product roadmap=E2=80=9D? Surely writing that sentence is more fun for Meta=
=E2=80=99s lawyers than whatever else they=E2=80=99ve got going on in their=
 day, even if it is technically less important.
The corollary to =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D is that e=
verything is also insider trading, and there are obvious applications here.=
 What if you show up at a Brazilian jiu-jitsu tournament to find that you a=
re fighting Mark Zuckerberg? If you knock him out, can you run to your Robi=
nhood account and short Meta stock before the ambulance gets there? (Can yo=
u short the stock=C2=A0before=C2=A0the match if you just know that you=E2=
=80=99re huge and will knock him out? Do you then fight dirty?) Brazilian j=
iu-jitsu tournaments now have a unique ability to=C2=A0create=C2=A0material=
 nonpublic information about Meta stock; what if someone uses it?

 =20
   =20
      Mortgage mark-to-market
   =20
 =20

At the Wall Street Journal, James Mackintosh has a fun column about the fac=
t that a lot of US homeowners
  [3]
 are sitting on big mark-to-market gains on their home mortgages. If you bo=
rrowed $500,000 to buy a house at 3% interest for 30 years, and then mortga=
ge rates went up to 8%, that mortgage is now arguably worth just $287,000.
  [4]
=C2=A0Your debt went from $500,000 to $287,000, so your net worth increased=
 by $223,000. Mackintosh writes:

Apply the logic used in the market, and there=E2=80=99s been a transfer of =
well over $1 trillion in wealth from banks and bondholders to borrowers as =
rates have soared=E2=80=94a gain in wealth widely ignored by the beneficiar=
ies. ...
In a world without financial frictions, the average borrower would see that=
 they were tens of thousands of dollars richer as a result. Those who secur=
ed a sub-3% rate for the full 30 years on an average-size mortgage are more=
 than $100,000 better off.
The problem: In the real world, the wealth gain doesn=E2=80=99t show up any=
where. That=E2=80=99s already changed the behavior of homeowners, who cling=
 to homes they would otherwise sell in order to keep the mortgage. It also =
means it makes sense to keep both debt and savings for financial=E2=80=94no=
t just tax=E2=80=94reasons, because the savings earn more than you pay on t=
he mortgage.

As a former financial engineer I find this situation a bit offensive: There=
=E2=80=99s $1 trillion of newly created (well, transferred) value, and nobo=
dy can do anything about it? Why isn=E2=80=99t someone building a product? =
We talked a while back about  assumable mortgages, which are one way to unl=
ock this value, but which are not broadly available. But really the temptin=
g product is:
=09You have a $500,000 mortgage that is now worth $287,000.=09You go to you=
r bank and say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll give you $300,000 for it.=E2=80=9D=09T=
he bank is like =E2=80=9Cfine okay that works.=E2=80=9D

The bank is better off: It gets $300,000 for an asset worth $287,000. Are y=
ou better off? Well, you have paid $300,000 to extinguish a $500,000 debt, =
so you=E2=80=99ve saved a lot of money over the life of the loan,
  [5]
=C2=A0though on an after-tax time-value-of-money basis it=E2=80=99s not cle=
ar that you=E2=80=99re better off. (You could have put the $300,000 in a sa=
vings account earning 4.5%, etc.)
The main benefit, for you, is=C2=A0if you want to move:=C2=A0Normally, if y=
ou want to move, you=C2=A0have to pay off the mortgage on your old house by=
 paying the full $500,000, and then, unless you can pay cash, you=C2=A0have=
 to get a new mortgage on your new house, and=C2=A0that=C2=A0mortgage will =
cost 8% or whatever. That=E2=80=99s why homeowners =E2=80=9Ccling to homes =
they would otherwise sell in order to keep the mortgage=E2=80=9D: Moving wo=
uld require paying off the old 3% mortgage and taking out a new 8% one. Tha=
t would be a lot more palatable if you could pay off the old 3% mortgage at=
 a huge discount reflecting its market value =E2=80=94=C2=A0if, effectively=
, you could pay it off at an 8% yield.
Obviously this product does not exist much, for several extremely good reas=
ons:
=09Your bank probably doesn=E2=80=99t actually own your mortgage: It probab=
ly sliced it into mortgage-backed securities and sold them to investors, so=
 there=E2=80=99s no one who owns your whole mortgage and can negotiate with=
 you, even if it were in their best interests to do so.=09Even if your bank=
 does own your mortgage, there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that it accounts f=
or it on a held-to-maturity basis, meaning that, while the bank=C2=A0knows=
=C2=A0the mortgage is only worth $287,000, it reflects it on its balance sh=
eet at $500,000. (Here is a Business=C2=A0Insider story about how =E2=80=9C=
US banks are sitting on an estimated $650 billion in unrealized losses on t=
heir bond holdings.=E2=80=9D) Selling it to you for $300,000 would be an ec=
onomic profit for the bank, but an accounting loss. And the bank cares a lo=
t about accounting: It=E2=80=99s really important, for the bank, to be solv=
ent on an accounting basis, and it will turn down economically profitable t=
rades to stay that way.=09It would be bad for the banking/mortgage system i=
f this were a thing. The way US mortgages mostly work is that you borrow at=
 a fixed rate for 30 years, but you can prepay at any time, and most people=
 do, because they move: Unless you actually stay in a house for 30 years, y=
ou will end up paying off your mortgage early. So in this example, your ban=
k knows that you will probably move eventually, so they=E2=80=99ll get thei=
r $500,000 back before the 30 years are up, so taking just $300,000 now is =
a bad trade. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll pay you $300,000 now for this mortgage s=
o I can move,=E2=80=9D you say to the bank, =E2=80=9Cand if you say no then=
 I will just stay here and pay my mortgage for 30 years=C2=A0 and you=E2=80=
=99ll be worse off,=E2=80=9D but the bank knows you are bluffing. So they s=
ay no, and you move anyway in two years, and they get their $500,000 back.

Still if you could build a product like this
  [6]
=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s like a trillion-dollar market, get on that.

