      Sentiment analysis
   =20
 =20

We   talked yesterday about how investors are increasingly employing robots=
 to analyze corporate executives=E2=80=99 tone of voice on earnings calls. =
But meanwhile corporate executives are analyzing analysts=E2=80=99 tone of =
voice on earnings calls, and it is making them sad. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   R=
edd Brown reports:

=E2=80=9CGood quarter,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccongratulations=E2=80=9D and simil=
ar plaudits are drying up on quarterly earnings calls for S&P 500 companies=
, setting up 2023 for the biggest such annual decline since the Great Reces=
sion. The drop is even more pronounced when compared with the pandemic era,=
 running 35% below the average pace in the previous three years. =E2=80=A6
The slump in congratulatory remarks may point to increasingly concerned inv=
estors heading into 2024 as the risk of inflation remains sticky, potential=
ly putting more pressure on policymakers. ...
And senior executives do care whether or not Wall Street research firms pat=
 them on the back. =E2=80=9COne hundred percent, we take notice of it,=E2=
=80=9D said Gina Mastantuono, chief financial officer of ServiceNow Inc. =
=E2=80=9CWe are very mindful of feedback,=E2=80=9D she said. Santa Clara-ba=
sed software provider ServiceNow has received over 150 plaudits over the la=
st five years, the most among members of the S&P 500, though the amount of =
kudos it received this quarter fell to seven from 12 a year ago.

There is a chart, counting =E2=80=9Cgood quarter,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cgreat q=
uarter,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Ccongrats=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccongratulations=E2=
=80=9D by quarter back through 2019. I wonder if anyone trades on this as a=
 signal. Not, like, for the stock, but for macro trading; is a downturn in =
=E2=80=9Cgreat quarter guys=E2=80=9D a leading indicator of recession? Of r=
ecovery? Anyway I wrote yesterday that the obvious solution, for conference=
 calls, is for investors and analysts to use robots to ask the questions, a=
nd for companies to use robots to answer them. That probably solves this pr=
oblem: Maybe the analyst-robots would not say =E2=80=9Cgreat quarter guys,=
=E2=80=9D but the executive-robots would not be offended.

