<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the Wall Street Journal, James Mackintosh <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33367080.258416/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2ludmVzdGluZy90aGUtdHJpbGxpb24tZG9sbGFyLX=
dpbi1oaWRpbmctaW4teW91ci1tb3J0Z2FnZS1hZTFjZDIxZT9tb2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3Mz/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB394290f9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">has a fun column</a> about the fact =
that a lot of US homeowners<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> are sitting on big mark-to-market gains on their home mortgages. If yo=
u borrowed $500,000 to buy a house at 3% interest for 30 years, and then mo=
rtgage rates went up to 8%, that mortgage is now arguably worth just $287,0=
00.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Your debt went from $500,000 to $287,000, so your net worth incre=
ased by $223,000. Mackintosh writes:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Apply the logic used in the market, and there=
=E2=80=99s been a transfer of well over $1 trillion in wealth from banks an=
d bondholders to borrowers as rates have soared=E2=80=94a gain in wealth wi=
dely ignored by the beneficiaries. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a world without financial frictions, the av=
erage borrower would see that they were tens of thousands of dollars richer=
 as a result. Those who secured a sub-3% rate for the full 30 years on an a=
verage-size mortgage are more than $100,000 better off.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem: In the real world, the wealth gai=
n doesn=E2=80=99t show up anywhere. That=E2=80=99s already changed the beha=
vior of homeowners, who cling to homes they would otherwise sell in order t=
o keep the mortgage. It also means it makes sense to keep both debt and sav=
ings for financial=E2=80=94not just tax=E2=80=94reasons, because the saving=
s earn more than you pay on the mortgage.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a former financial engineer I find this sit=
uation a bit offensive: There=E2=80=99s $1 trillion of newly created (well,=
 transferred) value, and nobody can do anything about it? Why isn=E2=80=99t=
 someone building a product? We talked a while back about <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33367080.258416/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMTMveWllbGRzdHJlZXQtbWlzc2=
VkLWEtYm9hdD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMTE0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0b=
V9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzExMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1=
ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7251425c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> assumable mortgages</a>, wh=
ich are one way to unlock this value, but which are not broadly available. =
But really the tempting product is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have a $500,000 mortgage that is =
now worth $287,000.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You go to your=
 bank and say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll give you $300,000 for it.=E2=80=9D</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The bank is like =E2=80=9Cfine okay th=
at works.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank is better off: It gets $300,000 for a=
n asset worth $287,000. Are you better off? Well, you have paid $300,000 to=
 extinguish a $500,000 debt, so you=E2=80=99ve saved a lot of money over th=
e life of the loan,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0though on an after-tax time-value-of-money basis it=E2=80=99s not=
 clear that you=E2=80=99re better off. (You could have put the $300,000 in =
a savings account earning 4.5%, etc.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main benefit, for you, is=C2=A0<em>if you =
want to move:=C2=A0</em>Normally, if you want to move, you=C2=A0have to pay=
 off the mortgage on your old house by paying the full $500,000, and then, =
unless you can pay cash, you=C2=A0have to get a new mortgage on your new ho=
use, and=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>mortgage will cost 8% or whatever. That=E2=
=80=99s why homeowners =E2=80=9Ccling to homes they would otherwise sell in=
 order to keep the mortgage=E2=80=9D: Moving would require paying off the o=
ld 3% mortgage and taking out a new 8% one. That would be a lot more palata=
ble if you could pay off the old 3% mortgage at a huge discount reflecting =
its market value =E2=80=94=C2=A0if, effectively, you could pay it off at an=
 8% yield.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously this product does not exist much, fo=
r several extremely good reasons:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your bank probably doesn=E2=80=99t ac=
tually own your mortgage: It probably sliced it into mortgage-backed securi=
ties and sold them to investors, so there=E2=80=99s no one who owns your wh=
ole mortgage and can negotiate with you, even if it were in their best inte=
rests to do so.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Even if your bank =
does own your mortgage, there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that it accounts fo=
r it on a held-to-maturity basis, meaning that, while the bank=C2=A0<em>kno=
ws=C2=A0</em>the mortgage is only worth $287,000, it reflects it on its bal=
ance sheet at $500,000. (Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/33367080.258416/aHR0cHM6Ly9tYXJrZXRzLmJ1c2luZXNzaW5zaWRlci5j=
b20vbmV3cy9ib25kcy9ib25kLW1hcmtldC1jcmFzaC1iYW5rcy11bnJlYWxpemVkLWxvc3Nlcy1=
0cmVhc3VyeXMtcmF0ZXMtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC0yMDIzLTEx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
59814a03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">a Business=C2=A0Insider story</a> about how =E2=80=9CUS b=
anks are sitting on an estimated $650 billion in unrealized losses on their=
 bond holdings.=E2=80=9D) Selling it to you for $300,000 would be an econom=
ic profit for the bank, but an accounting loss. And the bank cares a lot ab=
out accounting: It=E2=80=99s really important, for the bank, to be solvent =
on an accounting basis, and it will turn down economically profitable trade=
s to stay that way.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It would be ba=
d for the banking/mortgage system if this were a thing. The way US mortgage=
s mostly work is that you borrow at a fixed rate for 30 years, but you can =
prepay at any time, and most people do, because they move: Unless you actua=
lly stay in a house for 30 years, you will end up paying off your mortgage =
early. So in this example, your bank knows that you will probably move even=
tually, so they=E2=80=99ll get their $500,000 back before the 30 years are =
up, so taking just $300,000 now is a bad trade. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll pay y=
ou $300,000 now for this mortgage so I can move,=E2=80=9D you say to the ba=
nk, =E2=80=9Cand if you say no then I will just stay here and pay my mortga=
ge for 30 years=C2=A0 and you=E2=80=99ll be worse off,=E2=80=9D but the ban=
k knows you are bluffing. So they say no, and you move anyway in two years,=
 and they get their $500,000 back.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still if you could build a product like this<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s like a trillion-dollar market, get on that.</p>
